# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crypto
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The **Advanced Encryption Standard** (**AES**), also known by its original name **Rijndael** (Dutch pronunciation: [ˈrɛindaːl], *RAIN-dahl*), is a specification for the encryption of electronic data established by the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) in 2001.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is a variant of the Rijndael block cipher developed by two Belgian cryptographers, Joan Daemen and Vincent Rijmen, who submitted a proposal to NIST during the AES selection process.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Rijndael is a family of ciphers with different key and block sizes.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] For AES, NIST selected three members of the Rijndael family, each with a block size of 128 bits, but three different key lengths: 128, 192 and 256 bits.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has been adopted by the US government.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] It supersedes the Data Encryption Standard (DES), which was published in 1977.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The algorithm described by AES is a symmetric-key algorithm, meaning the same key is used for both encrypting and decrypting the data.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In the United States, AES was announced by the NIST as the US FIPS PUB 197 (FIPS 197) standard on November 26, 2001.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This announcement followed a five-year standardization process in which fifteen competing designs were presented and evaluated, before the Rijndael cipher was selected as the most suitable.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is included in the ISO/IEC 18033-3 standard.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES became effective as a US federal government standard on May 26, 2002, after approval by US secretary of commerce Donald Evans.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is available in many different encryption packages, and is the first (and only) publicly accessible cipher approved by the US National Security Agency (NSA) for top secret information when used in an NSA approved cryptographic module.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is based on a design principle known as a substitution–permutation network, and is efficient in both software and hardware.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Unlike its predecessor DES, AES does not use a Feistel network.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES is a variant of Rijndael, with a fixed block size of 128 bits, and a key size of 128, 192, or 256 bits.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] By contrast, Rijndael *per se* is specified with block and key sizes that may be any multiple of 32 bits, with a minimum of 128 and a maximum of 256 bits.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Most AES calculations are done in a particular finite field.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The key size used for an AES cipher specifies the number of transformation rounds that convert the input, called the plaintext, into the final output, called the ciphertext.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Each round consists of several processing steps, including one that depends on the encryption key itself.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] A set of reverse rounds are applied to transform ciphertext back into the original plaintext using the same encryption key.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] ShiftRows – a transposition step where the last three rows of the state are shifted cyclically a certain number of steps.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] MixColumns – a linear mixing operation which operates on the columns of the state, combining the four bytes in each column.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In the SubBytes step, each byte *ai,j* in the *state* array is replaced with a SubByte *S*(*ai,j*) using an 8-bit substitution box.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Before round 0, the *state* array is simply the plaintext/input.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This operation provides the non-linearity in the cipher.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The S-box used is derived from the multiplicative inverse over GF(28), known to have good non-linearity properties.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] To avoid attacks based on simple algebraic properties, the S-box is constructed by combining the inverse function with an invertible affine transformation.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The S-box is also chosen to avoid any fixed points (and so is a derangement), i.e., *S*(*ai,j*) ≠ *ai,j*, and also any opposite fixed points, i.e., *S*(*ai,j*) ⊕ *ai,j* ≠ FF16.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] While performing the decryption, the InvSubBytes step (the inverse of SubBytes) is used, which requires first taking the inverse of the affine transformation and then finding the multiplicative inverse.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The ShiftRows step operates on the rows of the state; it cyclically shifts the bytes in each row by a certain offset.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] For AES, the first row is left unchanged.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Each byte of the second row is shifted one to the left.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Similarly, the third and fourth rows are shifted by offsets of two and three respectively.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In this way, each column of the output state of the ShiftRows step is composed of bytes from each column of the input state.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The importance of this step is to avoid the columns being encrypted independently, in which case AES would degenerate into four independent block ciphers.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In the MixColumns step, the four bytes of each column of the state are combined using an invertible linear transformation.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The MixColumns function takes four bytes as input and outputs four bytes, where each input byte affects all four output bytes.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Together with ShiftRows, MixColumns provides diffusion in the cipher.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Matrix multiplication is composed of multiplication and addition of the entries.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Entries are bytes treated as coefficients of polynomial of order *x*7.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Multiplication is modulo irreducible polynomial *x*8 + *x*4 + *x*3 + *x* + 1.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] If processed bit by bit, then, after shifting, a conditional XOR with 1B16 should be performed if the shifted value is larger than FF16 (overflow must be corrected by subtraction of generating polynomial).
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] These are special cases of the usual multiplication in GF(28).
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The coefficients are displayed in their hexadecimal equivalent of the binary representation of bit polynomials from GF(28)[*x*].
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The MixColumns step can also be viewed as a multiplication by the shown particular MDS matrix in the finite field GF(28).
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This process is described further in the article Rijndael MixColumns.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In the AddRoundKey step, the subkey is combined with the state.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] For each round, a subkey is derived from the main key using Rijndael's key schedule; each subkey is the same size as the state.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The subkey is added by combining of the state with the corresponding byte of the subkey using bitwise XOR.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] On systems with 32-bit or larger words, it is possible to speed up execution of this cipher by combining the SubBytes and ShiftRows steps with the MixColumns step by transforming them into a sequence of table lookups.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This requires four 256-entry 32-bit tables (together occupying 4096 bytes).
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] A round can then be performed with 16 table lookup operations and 12 32-bit exclusive-or operations, followed by four 32-bit exclusive-or operations in the AddRoundKey step.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Alternatively, the table lookup operation can be performed with a single 256-entry 32-bit table (occupying 1024 bytes) followed by circular rotation operations.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Using a byte-oriented approach, it is possible to combine the SubBytes, ShiftRows, and MixColumns steps into a single round operation.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The National Security Agency (NSA) reviewed all the AES finalists, including Rijndael, and stated that all of them were secure enough for US Government non-classified data.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has 10 rounds for 128-bit keys, 12 rounds for 192-bit keys, and 14 rounds for 256-bit keys.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] More recent guidance from the NSA, however, only allows classified information to be encrypted with 256-bit key lengths.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] 128-bit and 192-bits is no longer sufficient for the encryption of classified information.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] For cryptographers, a cryptographic "break" is anything faster than a brute-force attack – i.e., performing one trial decryption for each possible key in sequence .
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] A break can thus include results that are infeasible with current technology.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Despite being impractical, theoretical breaks can sometimes provide insight into vulnerability patterns.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The largest successful publicly known brute-force attack against a widely implemented block-cipher encryption algorithm was against a 64-bit RC5 key by distributed.net in 2006.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The key space increases by a factor of 2 for each additional bit of key length, and if every possible value of the key is equiprobable; this translates into a doubling of the average brute-force key search time with every additional bit of key length.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This implies that the effort of a brute-force search increases exponentially with key length.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Key length in itself does not imply security against attacks, since there are ciphers with very long keys that have been found to be vulnerable.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES has a fairly simple algebraic framework.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In 2002, a theoretical attack, named the "XSL attack", was announced by Nicolas Courtois and Josef Pieprzyk, purporting to show a weakness in the AES algorithm, partially due to the low complexity of its nonlinear components.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Since then, other papers have shown that the attack, as originally presented, is unworkable; see XSL attack on block ciphers.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] By 2006, the best known attacks were on 7 rounds for 128-bit keys, 8 rounds for 192-bit keys, and 9 rounds for 256-bit keys.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Until May 2009, the only successful published attacks against the full AES were side-channel attacks on some specific implementations.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In 2009, a new related-key attack was discovered that exploits the simplicity of AES's key schedule and has a complexity of 2119.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In December 2009 it was improved to 299.5.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This is a follow-up to an attack discovered earlier in 2009 by Alex Biryukov, Dmitry Khovratovich, and Ivica Nikolić, with a complexity of 296 for one out of every 235 keys.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] However, related-key attacks are not of concern in any properly designed cryptographic protocol, as a properly designed protocol (i.e., implementational software) will take care not to allow related keys, essentially by constraining an attacker's means of selecting keys for relatedness.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Another attack was blogged by Bruce Schneier on July 30, 2009, and released as a preprint on August 3, 2009.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] 256-bit AES uses 14 rounds, so these attacks are not effective against full AES.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The practicality of these attacks with stronger related keys has been criticized, for instance, by the paper on chosen-key-relations-in-the-middle attacks on AES-128 authored by Vincent Rijmen in 2010.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In November 2009, the first known-key distinguishing attack against a reduced 8-round version of AES-128 was released as a preprint.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This known-key distinguishing attack is an improvement of the rebound, or the start-from-the-middle attack, against AES-like permutations, which view two consecutive rounds of permutation as the application of a so-called Super-S-box.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] It works on the 8-round version of AES-128, with a time complexity of 248, and a memory complexity of 232.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] 128-bit AES uses 10 rounds, so this attack is not effective against full AES-128.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The first key-recovery attacks on full AES were by Andrey Bogdanov, Dmitry Khovratovich, and Christian Rechberger, and were published in 2011.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The attack is a biclique attack and is faster than brute force by a factor of about four.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] It requires 2126.2 operations to recover an AES-128 key.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This result has been further improved to 2126.0 for AES-128, 2189.9 for AES-192, and 2254.3 for AES-256 by Biaoshuai Tao and Hongjun Wu in a 2015 paper, which are the current best results in key recovery attack against AES.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This is a very small gain, as a 126-bit key (instead of 128 bits) would still take billions of years to brute force on current and foreseeable hardware.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Also, the authors calculate the best attack using their technique on AES with a 128-bit key requires storing 288 bits of data.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] That works out to about 38 trillion terabytes of data, which was more than all the data stored on all the computers on the planet in 2016.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] A paper in 2015 later improved the space complexity to 256 bits, which is 9007 terabytes (while still keeping a time complexity of approximately 2126).
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] According to the Snowden documents, the NSA is doing research on whether a cryptographic attack based on tau statistic may help to break AES.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] At present, there is no known practical attack that would allow someone without knowledge of the key to read data encrypted by AES when correctly implemented.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Side-channel attacks do not attack the cipher as a black box, and thus are not related to cipher security as defined in the classical context, but are important in practice.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] They attack implementations of the cipher on hardware or software systems that inadvertently leak data.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] There are several such known attacks on various implementations of AES.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Bernstein announced a cache-timing attack that he used to break a custom server that used OpenSSL's AES encryption.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The attack required over 200 million chosen plaintexts.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The custom server was designed to give out as much timing information as possible (the server reports back the number of machine cycles taken by the encryption operation).
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In October 2005, Dag Arne Osvik, Adi Shamir and Eran Tromer presented a paper demonstrating several cache-timing attacks against the implementations in AES found in OpenSSL and Linux's `dm-crypt` partition encryption function.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] One attack was able to obtain an entire AES key after only 800 operations triggering encryptions, in a total of 65 milliseconds.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This attack requires the attacker to be able to run programs on the same system or platform that is performing AES.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In December 2009 an attack on some hardware implementations was published that used differential fault analysis and allows recovery of a key with a complexity of 232.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] In November 2010, Endre Bangerter, David Gullasch and Stephan Krenn published a paper which described a practical approach to a "near real time" recovery of secret keys from AES-128 without the need for either cipher text or plaintext.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The approach also works on AES-128 implementations that use compression tables, such as OpenSSL.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Like some earlier attacks, this one requires the ability to run unprivileged code on the system performing the AES encryption, which may be achieved by malware infection far more easily than commandeering the root account.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The proposed attack requires standard user privilege and key-retrieval algorithms run under a minute.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Many modern CPUs have built-in hardware instructions for AES, which protect against timing-related side-channel attacks.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-256 is considered to be quantum resistant, as it has similar quantum resistance to AES-128's resistance against traditional, non-quantum, attacks at 128 bits of security.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-192 and AES-128 are not considered quantum resistant due to their smaller key sizes.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] AES-192 has a strength of 96 bits against quantum attacks and AES-128 has 64 bits of strength against quantum attacks, making them both insecure.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The Cryptographic Module Validation Program (CMVP) is operated jointly by the United States Government's National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Computer Security Division and the Communications Security Establishment (CSE) of the Government of Canada.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The use of cryptographic modules validated to NIST FIPS 140-2 is required by the United States Government for encryption of all data that has a classification of Sensitive but Unclassified (SBU) or above.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The Government of Canada also recommends the use of FIPS 140 validated cryptographic modules in unclassified applications of its departments.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Although NIST publication 197 ("FIPS 197") is the unique document that covers the AES algorithm, vendors typically approach the CMVP under FIPS 140 and ask to have several algorithms (such as Triple DES or SHA1) validated at the same time.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Therefore, it is rare to find cryptographic modules that are uniquely FIPS 197 validated and NIST itself does not generally take the time to list FIPS 197 validated modules separately on its public web site.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Instead, FIPS 197 validation is typically just listed as an "FIPS approved: AES" notation (with a specific FIPS 197 certificate number) in the current list of FIPS 140 validated cryptographic modules.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The Cryptographic Algorithm Validation Program (CAVP) allows for independent validation of the correct implementation of the AES algorithm.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Successful validation results in being listed on the NIST validations page.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This testing is a pre-requisite for the FIPS 140-2 module validation.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] However, successful CAVP validation in no way implies that the cryptographic module implementing the algorithm is secure.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] A cryptographic module lacking FIPS 140-2 validation or specific approval by the NSA is not deemed secure by the US Government and cannot be used to protect government data.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] FIPS 140-2 validation is challenging to achieve both technically and fiscally.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] There is a standardized battery of tests as well as an element of source code review that must be passed over a period of a few weeks.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] The cost to perform these tests through an approved laboratory can be significant (e.g., well over US$30,000) and does not include the time it takes to write, test, document and prepare a module for validation.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] After validation, modules must be re-submitted and re-evaluated if they are changed in any way.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] This can vary from simple paperwork updates if the security functionality did not change to a more substantial set of re-testing if the security functionality was impacted by the change.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] Test vectors are a set of known ciphers for a given input and key.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] NIST distributes the reference of AES test vectors as AES Known Answer Test (KAT) Vectors.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] High speed and low RAM requirements were some of the criteria of the AES selection process.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] As the chosen algorithm, AES performed well on a wide variety of hardware, from 8-bit smart cards to high-performance computers.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] On a Pentium Pro, AES encryption requires 18 clock cycles per byte (cpb), equivalent to a throughput of about 11 MiB/s for a 200 MHz processor.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] On Intel Core and AMD Ryzen CPUs supporting AES-NI instruction set extensions, throughput can be multiple GiB/s.
[src:crypto/advanced-encryption-standard] On an Intel Westmere CPU, AES encryption using AES-NI takes about 1.3 cpb for AES-128, and 1.8 cpb for AES-256.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Traditionally, secure encrypted communication between two parties required that they first exchange keys by some secure physical means, such as paper key lists transported by a trusted courier.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The Diffie–Hellman key exchange method allows two parties that have no prior knowledge of each other to jointly establish a shared secret key over an insecure channel.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] This key can then be used to encrypt subsequent communications using a symmetric-key cipher.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Diffie–Hellman is used to secure a variety of Internet services.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] However, research published in October 2015 suggests that the parameters in use for many DH Internet applications at that time were not strong enough to prevent compromise by very well-funded attackers, such as the security services of some countries.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The scheme was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman in 1976, but in 1997 it was revealed that James H.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Williamson of GCHQ, the British signals intelligence agency, had previously shown in 1969 how public-key cryptography could be achieved.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Although Diffie–Hellman key exchange itself is a non-authenticated key-agreement protocol, it provides the basis for a variety of authenticated protocols, and is used to provide forward secrecy in Transport Layer Security's ephemeral modes (referred to as EDH or DHE depending on the cipher suite).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Forward secrecy results from the use of ephemeral keys: the private keys are discarded once key agreement is complete, making them safe from later compromise.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Ephemeral keys are practical because it is computationally cheap to create public-private key pairs suitable for use with Diffie-Hellman exchange.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The method was followed shortly after by the RSA cryptosystem, an implementation of public-key cryptography using asymmetric algorithms.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Expired US patent 4200770 from 1977 describes the now public-domain algorithm.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] It credits Hellman, Diffie, and Merkle as inventors.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Diffie–Hellman key exchange establishes a shared secret between two parties that can be used for secret communication for exchanging data over a public network.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The process begins by having the two parties, Alice and Bob, publicly agree on an arbitrary starting color that does not need to be kept secret.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Each person also selects a secret color that they keep to themselves – in this case, red and cyan.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The crucial part of the process is that Alice and Bob each mix their own secret color together with their mutually shared color, resulting in orange-tan and light-blue mixtures respectively, and then publicly exchange the two mixed colors.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Finally, each of them mixes the color they received from the partner with their own private color.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The result is a final color mixture (yellow-brown in this case) that is identical to their partner's final color mixture.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] If a third party listened to the exchange, they would only know the common color (yellow) and the first mixed colors (orange-tan and light-blue), but it would be very hard for them to find out the final secret color (yellow-brown).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bringing the analogy back to a real-life exchange using large numbers rather than colors, this determination is computationally expensive; it is impossible to compute in a practical amount of time even for modern supercomputers.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The simplest and the original implementation, later formalized as **Finite Field Diffie–Hellman** in RFC 7919, of the protocol uses the multiplicative group of integers modulo *p*, where *p* is prime, and *g* is a primitive root modulo *p*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] To guard against potential vulnerabilities, it is recommended to use prime numbers of at least 2048 bits in length.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] This increases the difficulty for an adversary attempting to compute the discrete logarithm and compromise the shared secret.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] These two values are chosen in this way to ensure that the resulting shared secret can take on any value from 1 to *p* − 1.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Here is an example of the protocol, with non-secret values in blue, and secret values in **red**.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice and Bob now share a secret (the number 18).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] All the other values – *p*, *g*, *ga* mod *p*, and *gb* mod *p* – are sent in the clear.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The strength of the scheme comes from the fact that *gab* mod *p* = *gba* mod *p* take extremely long times to compute by any known classical algorithm just from the knowledge of *p*, *g*, *ga* mod *p*, and *gb* mod *p*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Such a function that is easy to compute but hard to invert is called a one-way function.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Once Alice and Bob compute the shared secret they can use it as an encryption key, known only to them, for sending messages across the same open communications channel.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Of course, much larger values of *a*, *b*, and *p* would be needed to make this example secure, since there are only 23 possible results of *n* mod 23.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] However, if *p* is a prime of at least 600 digits, then even the fastest modern computers using the fastest known algorithm cannot find *a* given only *g*, *p* and *ga* mod *p*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Such a problem is called the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The computation of *ga* mod *p* is known as modular exponentiation and can be done efficiently even for large numbers.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Note that *g* need not be large at all, and in practice is usually a small integer (like 2, 3, ...).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The chart below depicts who knows what, again with non-secret values in blue, and secret values in **red**.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Here Eve is an eavesdropper – she watches what is sent between Alice and Bob, but she does not alter the contents of their communications.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Now ***s*** is the shared secret key and it is known to both Alice and Bob, but *not* to Eve.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Note that it is not helpful for Eve to compute *AB*, which equals *g****a***+***b*** mod p.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Note: It should be difficult for Alice to solve for Bob's private key or for Bob to solve for Alice's private key.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Eve may attempt to choose a public / private key pair that will make it easy for her to solve for Bob's private key.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice picks a random natural number *a* with 1 < *a* < *n*, and sends the element *ga* of *G* to Bob.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bob picks a random natural number *b* with 1 < *b* < *n*, and sends the element *gb* of *G* to Alice.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice computes the element (*gb*)*a* = *gba* of G.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bob computes the element (*ga*)*b* = *gab* of G.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Both Alice and Bob are now in possession of the group element *gab* = *gba*, which can serve as the shared secret key.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The group *G* satisfies the requisite condition for secure communication as long as there is no efficient algorithm for determining *gab* given *g*, *ga*, and *gb*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] For example, the elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman protocol is a variant that represents an element of G as a point on an elliptic curve instead of as an integer modulo n.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Variants using hyperelliptic curves have also been proposed.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The supersingular isogeny key exchange is a Diffie–Hellman variant that was designed to be secure against quantum computers, but it was broken in July 2022.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The used keys can either be ephemeral or static (long term) key, but could even be mixed, so called semi-static DH.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] These variants have different properties and hence different use cases.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] An overview over many variants and some also discussions can for example be found in NIST SP 800-56A.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] 2. static, static: Would generate a long term shared secret.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Does not provide forward secrecy, but implicit authenticity.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Since the keys are static it would for example not protect against replay-attacks.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] 3. ephemeral, static: For example, used in ElGamal encryption or Integrated Encryption Scheme (IES).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] If used in key agreement it could provide implicit one-sided authenticity (the ephemeral side could verify the authenticity of the static side).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] It is possible to use ephemeral and static keys in one key agreement to provide more security as for example shown in NIST SP 800-56A, but it is also possible to combine those in a single DH key exchange, which is then called triple DH (3-DH).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] In 1997 a kind of triple DH was proposed by Simon Blake-Wilson, Don Johnson and Alfred Menezes, which was improved by C.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Paterson in 2005 and shown to be secure.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The long term secret keys of Alice and Bob are denoted by *a* and *b* respectively, with public keys *A* and *B*, as well as the ephemeral key pairs (*x*, *X*) and (*y*, *Y*).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The long term public keys need to be transferred somehow.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] That can be done beforehand in a separate, trusted channel, or the public keys can be encrypted using some partial key agreement to preserve anonymity.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] For more of such details as well as other improvements like side channel protection or explicit key confirmation, as well as early messages and additional password authentication, see e.g.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] US patent "Advanced modular handshake for key agreement and optional authentication".
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] X3DH was initially proposed as part of the Double Ratchet Algorithm used in the Signal Protocol.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The protocol offers forward secrecy and cryptographic deniability.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice has an identity key IKA and an ephemeral key EKA.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bob has an identity key IKB, a signed prekey SPKB, and a one-time prekey OPKB.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bob first publishes his three keys to a server, which Alice downloads and verifies the signature on.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice then initiates the exchange to Bob.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Diffie–Hellman key agreement is not limited to negotiating a key shared by only two participants.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Any number of users can take part in an agreement by performing iterations of the agreement protocol and exchanging intermediate data (which does not itself need to be kept secret).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The parties generate their private keys, named *a*, *b*, and *c*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice computes *ga* mod *p* and sends it to Bob.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bob computes (*ga*)*b* mod *p* = *gab* mod *p* and sends it to Carol.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Carol computes (*gab*)*c* mod *p* = *gabc* mod *p* and uses it as her secret.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bob computes gb mod *p* and sends it to Carol.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Carol computes (*gb*)*c* mod *p* = *gbc* mod *p* and sends it to Alice.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice computes (*gbc*)*a* mod *p* = *gbca* mod *p* = *gabc* mod *p* and uses it as her secret.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Carol computes *gc* mod *p* and sends it to Alice.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Alice computes (*gc*)*a* mod *p* = *gca* mod *p* and sends it to Bob.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Bob computes (*gca*)*b* mod *p* = *gcab* mod *p* = *gabc* mod *p* and uses it as his secret.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] An eavesdropper has been able to see *ga* mod *p*, *gb* mod *p*, *gc* mod *p*, *gab* mod *p*, *gac* mod *p*, and *gbc* mod *p*, but cannot use any combination of these to efficiently reproduce *gabc* mod *p*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] These principles leave open various options for choosing in which order participants contribute to keys.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] However, this requires that every participant perform *N* modular exponentiations.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Participants A and B each perform one exponentiation, yielding *gefghab*, which they send to C and D, while C and D do the same, yielding *gefghcd*, which they send to A and B.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Participant A performs an exponentiation, yielding *gefghcda*, which it sends to B; similarly, B sends *gefghcdb* to A.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Participant A performs one final exponentiation, yielding the secret *gefghcdba* = *gabcdefgh*, while B does the same to get *gefghcdab* = *gabcdefgh*; again, C and D do similarly.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Participants E through H simultaneously perform the same operations using *gabcd* as their starting point.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Once this operation has been completed all participants will possess the secret *gabcdefgh*, but each participant will have performed only four modular exponentiations, rather than the eight implied by a simple circular arrangement.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The protocol is considered secure against eavesdroppers if *G* and *g* are chosen properly.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] In particular, the order of the group G must be large, particularly if the same group is used for large amounts of traffic.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The eavesdropper has to solve the Diffie–Hellman problem to obtain *g**ab*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] This is currently considered difficult for groups whose order is large enough.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] An efficient algorithm to solve the discrete logarithm problem would make it easy to compute *a* or *b* and solve the Diffie–Hellman problem, making this and many other public key cryptosystems insecure.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Fields of small characteristic may be less secure.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The order of *G* should have a large prime factor to prevent use of the Pohlig–Hellman algorithm to obtain *a* or *b*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] For this reason, a Sophie Germain prime *q* is sometimes used to calculate *p* = 2*q* + 1, called a safe prime, since the order of *G* is then only divisible by 2 and *q*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Sometimes *g* is chosen to generate the order *q* subgroup of *G*, rather than *G*, so that the Legendre symbol of *ga* never reveals the low order bit of *a*.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] A protocol using such a choice is for example IKEv2.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The generator *g* is often a small integer such as 2.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Because of the random self-reducibility of the discrete logarithm problem a small *g* is equally secure as any other generator of the same group.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] If Alice and Bob use random number generators whose outputs are not completely random and can be predicted to some extent, then it is much easier to eavesdrop.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] In the original description, the Diffie–Hellman exchange by itself does not provide authentication of the communicating parties and can be vulnerable to a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Mallory (an active attacker executing the man-in-the-middle attack) may establish two distinct key exchanges, one with Alice and the other with Bob, effectively masquerading as Alice to Bob, and vice versa, allowing her to decrypt, then re-encrypt, the messages passed between them.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Note that Mallory must be in the middle from the beginning and continuing to be so, actively decrypting and re-encrypting messages every time Alice and Bob communicate.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] If she arrives after the keys have been generated and the encrypted conversation between Alice and Bob has already begun, the attack cannot succeed.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] If she is ever absent, her previous presence is then revealed to Alice and Bob.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] They will know that all of their private conversations had been intercepted and decoded by someone in the channel.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] In most cases it will not help them get Mallory's private key, even if she used the same key for both exchanges.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] A method to authenticate the communicating parties to each other is generally needed to prevent this type of attack.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Variants of Diffie–Hellman, such as STS protocol, may be used instead to avoid these types of attacks.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] A CVE released in 2021 (*CVE-2002-20001*) disclosed a denial-of-service attack (DoS) against the protocol variants using ephemeral keys, called D(HE)at attack.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The attack exploits that the Diffie–Hellman key exchange allows attackers to send arbitrary numbers that are actually not public keys, triggering expensive modular exponentiation calculations on the victim's side.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] An attacker can exploit both vulnerabilities together.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The number field sieve algorithm, which is generally the most effective in solving the discrete logarithm problem, consists of four computational steps.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The first three steps only depend on the order of the group G, not on the specific number whose finite log is desired.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] It turns out that much Internet traffic uses one of a handful of groups that are of order 1024 bits or less.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] By precomputing the first three steps of the number field sieve for the most common groups, an attacker need only carry out the last step, which is much less computationally expensive than the first three steps, to obtain a specific logarithm.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The Logjam attack used this vulnerability to compromise a variety of Internet services that allowed the use of groups whose order was a 512-bit prime number, so called export grade.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The authors needed several thousand CPU cores for a week to precompute data for a single 512-bit prime.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Once that was done, individual logarithms could be solved in about a minute using two 18-core Intel Xeon CPUs.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] As estimated by the authors behind the Logjam attack, the much more difficult precomputation needed to solve the discrete log problem for a 1024-bit prime would cost on the order of $100 million, well within the budget of a large national intelligence agency such as the U.S.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The Logjam authors speculate that precomputation against widely reused 1024-bit DH primes is behind claims in leaked NSA documents that NSA is able to break much of current cryptography.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] To avoid these vulnerabilities, the Logjam authors recommend use of elliptic curve cryptography, for which no similar attack is known.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Failing that, they recommend that the order, *p*, of the Diffie–Hellman group should be at least 2048 bits.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] They estimate that the pre-computation required for a 2048-bit prime is 109 times more difficult than for 1024-bit primes.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Quantum computers can break public-key cryptographic schemes, such as RSA, finite-field DH and elliptic-curve DH key-exchange protocols, using Shor's algorithm for solving the factoring problem, the discrete logarithm problem, and the period-finding problem.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] A post-quantum variant of Diffie-Hellman algorithm was proposed in 2023, and relies on a combination of the quantum-resistant CRYSTALS-Kyber protocol, as well as the old elliptic curve X25519 protocol.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Public key encryption schemes based on the Diffie–Hellman key exchange have been proposed.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The first such scheme is the ElGamal encryption.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] A more modern variant is the Integrated Encryption Scheme.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Protocols that achieve forward secrecy generate new key pairs for each session and discard them at the end of the session.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] The Diffie–Hellman key exchange is a frequent choice for such protocols, because of its fast key generation.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] When Alice and Bob share a password, they may use a password-authenticated key agreement (PK) form of Diffie–Hellman to prevent man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] One simple scheme is to compare the hash of **s** concatenated with the password calculated independently on both ends of channel.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] A feature of these schemes is that an attacker can only test one specific password on each iteration with the other party, and so the system provides good security with relatively weak passwords.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] This approach is described in ITU-T Recommendation X.1035, which is used by the G.hn home networking standard.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] An example of such a protocol is the Secure Remote Password protocol.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] It is also possible to use Diffie–Hellman as part of a public key infrastructure, allowing Bob to encrypt a message so that only Alice will be able to decrypt it, with no prior communication between them other than Bob having trusted knowledge of Alice's public key.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] To send her a message, Bob chooses a random *b* and then sends Alice $g^{b}{\bmod {p}}$ (unencrypted) together with the message encrypted with symmetric key $(g^{a})^{b}{\bmod {p}}$ .
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Only Alice can determine the symmetric key and hence decrypt the message because only she has *a* (the private key).
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] A pre-shared public key also prevents man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] In practice, Diffie–Hellman is not used in this way, with RSA being the dominant public key algorithm.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] This is largely for historical and commercial reasons, namely that RSA Security created a certificate authority for key signing that became Verisign.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] Diffie–Hellman, as elaborated above, cannot directly be used to sign certificates.
[src:crypto/diffie-hellman-key-exchange] However, the ElGamal and DSA signature algorithms are mathematically related to it, as well as MQV, STS and the IKE component of the IPsec protocol suite for securing Internet Protocol communications.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:crypto/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:crypto/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:crypto/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:crypto/hmac] In cryptography, an **HMAC** (sometimes expanded as either **keyed-hash message authentication code** or **hash-based message authentication code**) is a specific type of message authentication code (MAC) involving a cryptographic hash function and a secret cryptographic key.
[src:crypto/hmac] As with any MAC, it may be used to simultaneously verify both the data integrity and authenticity of a message.
[src:crypto/hmac] An HMAC is a type of keyed hash function that can also be used in a key derivation scheme or a key stretching scheme.
[src:crypto/hmac] HMAC can provide authentication using a shared secret instead of using digital signatures with asymmetric cryptography.
[src:crypto/hmac] It trades off the need for a complex public key infrastructure by delegating the key exchange to the communicating parties, who are responsible for establishing and using a trusted channel to agree on the key prior to communication.
[src:crypto/hmac] Any cryptographic hash function, such as SHA-2 or SHA-3, may be used in the calculation of an HMAC; the resulting MAC algorithm is termed HMAC-*x*, where *x* is the hash function used (e.g.
[src:crypto/hmac] The cryptographic strength of the HMAC depends upon the cryptographic strength of the underlying hash function, the size of its hash output, and the size and quality of the key.
[src:crypto/hmac] HMAC uses two passes of hash computation.
[src:crypto/hmac] Before either pass, the secret key is used to derive two keys – inner and outer.
[src:crypto/hmac] Next, the first pass of the hash algorithm produces an internal hash derived from the message and the inner key.
[src:crypto/hmac] The second pass produces the final HMAC code derived from the inner hash result and the outer key.
[src:crypto/hmac] Thus the algorithm provides better immunity against length extension attacks.
[src:crypto/hmac] An iterative hash function (one that uses the Merkle–Damgård construction) breaks up a message into blocks of a fixed size and iterates over them with a compression function.
[src:crypto/hmac] For example, SHA-256 operates on 512-bit blocks.
[src:crypto/hmac] The size of the output of HMAC is the same as that of the underlying hash function (e.g., 256 and 512 bits in the case of SHA-256 and SHA3-512, respectively), although it can be truncated if desired.
[src:crypto/hmac] Instead, the message (encrypted or not) must be sent alongside the HMAC hash.
[src:crypto/hmac] Parties with the secret key will hash the message again themselves, and if it is authentic, the received and computed hashes will match.
[src:crypto/hmac] The definition and analysis of the HMAC construction was first published in 1996 in a paper by Mihir Bellare, Ran Canetti, and Hugo Krawczyk, and they also wrote RFC 2104 in 1997.
[src:crypto/hmac] The 1996 paper also defined a nested variant called NMAC (Nested MAC).
[src:crypto/hmac] FIPS PUB 198 generalizes and standardizes the use of HMACs.
[src:crypto/hmac] HMAC is used within the IPsec, SSH and TLS protocols and for JSON Web Tokens.
[src:crypto/hmac] ; either by padding to the right with 0s up to the block size, or by hashing down to less than or equal to the block size first and then padding to the right with zeros.
[src:crypto/hmac] is the block-sized outer padding, consisting of repeated bytes valued 0x5c.
[src:crypto/hmac] is the block-sized inner padding, consisting of repeated bytes valued 0x36.
[src:crypto/hmac] The following pseudocode demonstrates how HMAC may be implemented.
[src:crypto/hmac] The block size is 512 bits (64 bytes) when using one of the following hash functions: SHA-1, MD5, RIPEMD-128.
[src:crypto/hmac] The design of the HMAC specification was motivated by the existence of attacks on more trivial mechanisms for combining a key with a hash function.
[src:crypto/hmac] For example, one might assume the same security that HMAC provides could be achieved with MAC = **H**(*key* ∥ *message*).
[src:crypto/hmac] However, this method suffers from a serious flaw: with most hash functions, it is easy to append data to the message without knowing the key and obtain another valid MAC ("length-extension attack").
[src:crypto/hmac] Using MAC = **H**(*key* ∥ *message* ∥ *key*) is better, but various security papers have suggested vulnerabilities with this approach, even when two different keys are used.
[src:crypto/hmac] No known extension attacks have been found against the current HMAC specification which is defined as **H**(*key* ∥ **H**(*key* ∥ *message*)) because the outer application of the hash function masks the intermediate result of the internal hash.
[src:crypto/hmac] The values of *ipad* and *opad* are not critical to the security of the algorithm, but were defined in such a way to have a large Hamming distance from each other and so the inner and outer keys will have fewer bits in common.
[src:crypto/hmac] The security reduction of HMAC does require them to be different in at least one bit.
[src:crypto/hmac] The Keccak hash function, that was selected by NIST as the SHA-3 competition winner, does not need this nested approach and can be used to generate a MAC by simply prepending the key to the message, as it is not susceptible to length-extension attacks.
[src:crypto/hmac] The cryptographic strength of the HMAC depends upon the size of the secret key that is used and the security of the underlying hash function used.
[src:crypto/hmac] It has been proven that the security of an HMAC construction is directly related to security properties of the hash function used.
[src:crypto/hmac] The most common attack against HMACs is brute force to uncover the secret key.
[src:crypto/hmac] HMACs are substantially less affected by collisions than their underlying hashing algorithms alone.
[src:crypto/hmac] In particular, Mihir Bellare proved that HMAC is a pseudo-random function (PRF) under the sole assumption that the compression function is a PRF.
[src:crypto/hmac] Therefore, HMAC-MD5 does not suffer from the same weaknesses that have been found in MD5.
[src:crypto/hmac] RFC 2104 requires that "keys longer than *B* bytes are first hashed using *H*" which leads to a confusing pseudo-collision: if the key is longer than the hash block size (e.g.
[src:crypto/hmac] 64 bytes for SHA-1), then `HMAC(k, m)` is computed as `HMAC(H(k), m)`.
[src:crypto/hmac] This property is sometimes raised as a possible weakness of HMAC in password-hashing scenarios: it has been demonstrated that it's possible to find a long ASCII string and a random value whose hash will be also an ASCII string, and both values will produce the same HMAC output.
[src:crypto/hmac] In 2006, Jongsung Kim, Alex Biryukov, Bart Preneel, and Seokhie Hong showed how to distinguish HMAC with reduced versions of MD5 and SHA-1 or full versions of HAVAL, MD4, and SHA-0 from a random function or HMAC with a random function.
[src:crypto/hmac] Differential distinguishers allow an attacker to devise a forgery attack on HMAC.
[src:crypto/hmac] Furthermore, differential and rectangle distinguishers can lead to second-preimage attacks.
[src:crypto/hmac] HMAC with the full version of MD4 can be forged with this knowledge.
[src:crypto/hmac] These attacks do not contradict the security proof of HMAC, but provide insight into HMAC based on existing cryptographic hash functions.
[src:crypto/hmac] In 2009, Xiaoyun Wang *et al.* presented a distinguishing attack on HMAC-MD5 without using related keys.
[src:crypto/hmac] It can distinguish an instantiation of HMAC with MD5 from an instantiation with a random function with 297 queries with probability 0.87.
[src:crypto/hmac] In 2011 an informational RFC 6151 was published to summarize security considerations in MD5 and HMAC-MD5.
[src:crypto/hmac] In May 2011, RFC 6234 was published detailing the abstract theory and source code for SHA-based HMACs.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:crypto/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The **RSA** (**Rivest–Shamir–Adleman**) **cryptosystem** is a family of public-key cryptosystems (one of the oldest), widely used for secure data transmission.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The initialism "RSA" comes from the surnames of Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, who publicly described the algorithm in 1977.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] An equivalent system was developed secretly in 1973 at Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), the British signals intelligence agency, by the English mathematician Clifford Cocks.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] RSA is used in digital signature such as RSASSA-PSS or RSA-FDH, public-key encryption of very short messages (almost always a single-use symmetric key in a hybrid cryptosystem) such as RSAES-OAEP, and public-key key encapsulation.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] In RSA-based cryptography, a user's *private key*—which can be used to sign messages, or decrypt messages sent to that user—is a pair of large prime numbers chosen at random and kept secret.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] A user's *public key*—which can be used to verify messages from the user, or encrypt messages so that only that user can decrypt them—is the product of the prime numbers.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The security of RSA is related to the difficulty of factoring the product of two large prime numbers, the "factoring problem".
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Breaking RSA encryption is known as the RSA problem.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Whether it is as difficult as the factoring problem is an open question.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] There are no published methods to defeat the system if a large enough key is used.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The idea of an asymmetric public-private key cryptosystem is attributed to Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman, who published this concept in 1976.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] They also introduced digital signatures and attempted to apply number theory.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Their formulation used a shared-secret-key created from exponentiation of some number, modulo a prime number.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] However, they left open the problem of realizing a one-way function, possibly because the difficulty of factoring was not well-studied at the time.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Moreover, like Diffie-Hellman, RSA is based on modular exponentiation.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Leonard Adleman at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology made several attempts over the course of a year to create a function that was hard to invert.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Rivest and Shamir, as computer scientists, proposed many potential functions, while Adleman, as a mathematician, was responsible for finding their weaknesses.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] They tried many approaches, including "knapsack-based" and "permutation polynomials".
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] For a time, they thought what they wanted to achieve was impossible due to contradictory requirements.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] In April 1977, they spent Passover at the house of a student and drank a good deal of wine before returning to their homes at around midnight.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Rivest, unable to sleep, lay on the couch with a math textbook and started thinking about their one-way function.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] He spent the rest of the night formalizing his idea, and he had much of the paper ready by daybreak.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The algorithm is now known as RSA – the initials of their surnames in same order as their paper.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Clifford Cocks, an English mathematician working for the British intelligence agency Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), described a similar system in an internal document in 1973.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] However, given the relatively expensive computers needed to implement it at the time, it was considered to be mostly a curiosity and, as far as is publicly known, was never deployed.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] His ideas and concepts were not revealed until 1997 due to its top-secret classification.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Kid-RSA (KRSA) is a simplified, insecure public-key cipher published in 1997, designed for educational purposes.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Kid-RSA gives insight into RSA and other public-key ciphers, analogous to simplified DES.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] A patent describing the RSA algorithm was granted to MIT on 20 September 1983: U.S. patent 4,405,829 "Cryptographic communications system and method".
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] A detailed description of the algorithm was published in August 1977, in *Scientific American*'s Mathematical Games column.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] This preceded the patent's filing date of December 1977.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Consequently, the patent had no legal standing outside the United States.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Had Cocks' work been publicly known, a patent in the United States would not have been legal either.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] When the patent was issued, terms of patent were 17 years.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The patent was about to expire on 21 September 2000, but RSA Security released the algorithm to the public domain on 6 September 2000.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The RSA algorithm involves four steps: key generation, key distribution, public-key operation (used for encryption or verifying a signature), and private key operation (used for decryption or signing a message).
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The integers n and e form the public key and d is the private key.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The modular exponentiation to the power of e is used in encryption and in verifying signatures, and exponentiation to the power of d is used in decryption and in signing messages.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Compute *λ*(*n*), where λ is Carmichael's totient function.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Determine d as *d* ≡ *e*−1 (mod *λ*(*n*)); that is, d is the modular multiplicative inverse of e modulo *λ*(*n*).
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The *public key* consists of the modulus n and the public exponent e.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The *private key* consists of the private exponent d, which must be kept secret. p, q, and *λ*(*n*) must also be kept secret because they can be used to calculate d.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] In fact, they can all be discarded after d has been computed.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] In the original RSA paper, the Euler totient function *φ*(*n*) = (*p* − 1)(*q* − 1) is used instead of *λ*(*n*) for calculating the private exponent d.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Since *φ*(*n*) is always divisible by *λ*(*n*), the algorithm works as well.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The possibility of using Euler totient function results also from Lagrange's theorem applied to the multiplicative group of integers modulo *pq*.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] However, computing d modulo *φ*(*n*) will sometimes yield a result that is larger than necessary (i.e.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Any "oversized" private exponents not meeting this criterion may always be reduced modulo *λ*(*n*) to obtain a smaller equivalent exponent.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Note: The authors of the original RSA paper carry out the key generation by choosing d and then computing e as the modular multiplicative inverse of d modulo *φ*(*n*), whereas most current implementations of RSA, such as those following PKCS#1, do the reverse—choose e and compute d from it.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Since e can safely be small and fixed, whereas d must be chosen from a large enough space to resist attack, the modern approach can reduce the cost of the public-key operation without loss of security.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Suppose that Bob wants to send secret messages to Alice, or verify messages from Alice.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] If they decide to use RSA, Bob must know Alice's public key to encrypt his secret messages or verify Alice's messages, and Alice must use her private key to decrypt Bob's secret messages or sign her own messages.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] To enable Bob to send his encrypted messages or verify her future messages, Alice transmits her public key (*n*, *e*) to Bob via a reliable, but not necessarily secret, route.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Alice's private key (*d*) is never distributed.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] After Bob obtains Alice's public key, he can send a message M to Alice.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] To do it, he first turns M into an integer m, the padded plaintext, such that 0 ≤ *m* < *n*, by using an agreed-upon reversible protocol known as a padding scheme.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] This can be done reasonably quickly, even for very large numbers, using modular exponentiation.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Note that at least nine values of m will yield a ciphertext c equal to m, but this is very unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Given m, she can recover the original message M by reversing the padding scheme, or discard it as corrupted if the padding is invalid.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Choose any number 1 < *e* < 780 that is coprime to 780.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Choosing a prime number for e leaves us only to check that e is not a divisor of 780.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Both of these calculations can be computed efficiently using the square-and-multiply algorithm for modular exponentiation.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] In real-life situations the primes selected would be much larger; in our example it would be trivial to factor *n* = 3233 (obtained from the freely available public key) back to the primes p and q. e, also from the public key, is then inverted to get d, thus acquiring the private key.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Practical implementations use the Chinese remainder theorem to speed up the calculation using modulus of factors (mod *pq* using mod *p* and mod *q*).
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Suppose Alice wishes to send a signed message m to Bob.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] She produces a hash value *h* = hash(*m*) of the message m, raises it to the power of d (modulo n), and attaches *s* = *h**d* mod *n* as a "signature" to the message.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] When Bob receives the message m and signature s, he uses the same hash algorithm in conjunction with Alice's public key to compute *h* = hash(*m*).
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The modular exponentiation for signing and verification is the same underlying mathematics as for decryption and encryption, but all the other details of padding scheme for secure public-key encryption and hashing for secure digital signature are different.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The use of a hash, first proposed in 1978 by Michael O.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] The proof of the correctness of RSA is based on Fermat's little theorem, stating that *a**p* − 1 ≡ 1 (mod *p*) for any integer a and prime p, not dividing a.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] We want to show that $(m^{e})^{d}\equiv m{\pmod {pq}}$ for every integer m when p and q are distinct prime numbers and e and d are positive integers satisfying *ed* ≡ 1 (mod *λ*(*pq*)).
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] Since *λ*(*pq*) = lcm(*p* − 1, *q* − 1) is, by construction, divisible by both *p* − 1 and *q* − 1, we can write $ed-1=h(p-1)=k(q-1)$ for some nonnegative integers h and k.
[src:crypto/rsa-cryptosystem] To check whether two numbers, such as m*ed* and m, are congruent mod *pq*, it suffices (and in fact is equivalent) to check that they are congruent mod *p* and mod *q* separately.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] In cryptography, a **salt** is random data fed as an additional input to a one-way function that hashes data, a password or passphrase.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Salting helps defend against attacks that use precomputed tables (e.g. rainbow tables), by vastly growing the size of table needed for a successful attack.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] It also helps protect passwords that occur multiple times in a database, as a new salt is used for each password instance.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Additionally, salting does not place any burden on users.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Typically, a unique salt is randomly generated for each password.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The salt and the password (or its version after key stretching) are concatenated and fed to a cryptographic hash function, and the output hash value is then stored with the salt in a database.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The salt does not need to be encrypted, because knowing the salt would not help the attacker.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Salting is broadly used in cybersecurity, from Unix system credentials to Internet security.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Salts are related to cryptographic nonces.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Without a salt, identical passwords will map to identical hash values, which could make it easier for a hacker to guess the passwords from their hash value.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Instead, a salt is generated and appended to each password, which causes the resultant hash to output different values for the same original password.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The salt and hash are then stored in the database.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] To later test if a password a user enters is correct, the same process can be performed on it (appending that user's salt to the password and calculating the resultant hash): if the result does not match the stored hash, it could not have been the correct password that was entered.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] In practice, a salt is usually generated using a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator (CSPRNG).
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] CSPRNGs are designed to produce unpredictable random numbers which can be alphanumeric.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] While generally discouraged due to lower security, some systems use timestamps or simple counters as a source of salt.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Sometimes, a salt may be generated by combining a random value with additional information, such as a timestamp or user-specific data, to ensure uniqueness across different systems or time periods.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Using the same salt for all passwords is dangerous because a precomputed table which simply accounts for the salt will render the salt useless.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Generation of precomputed tables for databases with unique salts for every password is not viable because of the computational cost of doing so.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] But, if a common salt is used for all the entries, creating such a table (that accounts for the salt) then becomes a viable and possibly successful attack.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Because salt re-use can cause users with the same password to have the same hash, cracking a single hash can result in other passwords being compromised too.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] If a salt is too short, an attacker may precompute a table of every possible salt appended to every likely password.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Using a long salt ensures such a table would be prohibitively large.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] 16 bytes (128 bits) or more is generally sufficient to provide a large enough space of possible values, minimizing the risk of collisions (i.e., two different passwords ending up with the same salt).
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] To understand the difference between cracking a single password and a set of them, consider a file with users and their hashed passwords.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Then an attacker could pick a string, call it `attempt[0]`, and then compute `hash(attempt[0])`.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] A user whose hash stored in the file is `hash(attempt[0])` may or may not have password `attempt[0]`.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] However, even if `attempt[0]` is *not* the user's actual password, it will be accepted as if it were, because the system can only check passwords by computing the hash of the password entered and comparing it to the hash stored in the file.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Thus, each match cracks a user password, and the chance of a match rises with the number of passwords in the file.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] In contrast, if salts are used, the attacker would have to compute `hash(attempt[0] || salt[a])`, compare against entry A, then `hash(attempt[0] || salt[b])`, compare against entry B, and so on.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] This prevents any one attempt from cracking multiple passwords, given that salt re-use is avoided.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Salts also combat the use of precomputed tables for cracking passwords.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Such a table might simply map common passwords to their hashes, or it might do something more complex, like store the start and end points of a set of precomputed hash chains.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] In either case, salting can defend against the use of precomputed tables by lengthening hashes and having them draw from larger character sets, making it less likely that the table covers the resulting hashes.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] In particular, a precomputed table would need to cover the string `[salt + hash]` rather than simply `[hash]`.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The modern shadow password system, in which password hashes and other security data are stored in a non-public file, somewhat mitigates these concerns.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] However, they remain relevant in multi-server installations which use centralized password management systems to push passwords or password hashes to multiple systems.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Another (lesser) benefit of a salt is as follows: two users might choose the same string as their password.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Without a salt, this password would be stored as the same hash string in the password file.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] This would disclose the fact that the two accounts have the same password, allowing anyone who knows one of the account's passwords to access the other account.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] By salting the passwords with two random characters, even if two accounts use the same password, no one can discover this just by reading hashes.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Salting also makes it extremely difficult to determine if a person has used the same password for multiple systems.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Earlier versions of Unix used a password file `/etc/passwd` to store the hashes of salted passwords (passwords prefixed with two-character random salts).
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] In these older versions of Unix, the salt was also stored in the passwd file (as cleartext) together with the hash of the salted password.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The password file was publicly readable for all users of the system.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] This was necessary so that user-privileged software tools could find user names and other information.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The security of passwords is therefore protected only by the one-way functions (enciphering or hashing) used for the purpose.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Early Unix implementations limited passwords to eight characters and used a 12-bit salt, which allowed for 4,096 possible salt values.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] This was an appropriate balance for 1970s computational and storage costs.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The shadow password system is used to limit access to hashes and salt.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] The salt is eight characters, the hash is 86 characters, and the password length is effectively unlimited, barring stack overflow errors.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] It is common for a web application to store in a database the hash value of a user's password.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Without a salt, a successful SQL injection attack may yield easily crackable passwords.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Because many users re-use passwords for multiple sites, the use of a salt is an important component of overall web application security.
[src:crypto/salt-cryptography] Some additional references for using a salt to secure password hashes in specific languages or libraries (PHP, the .NET libraries, etc.) can be found in the external links section below.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-2 includes significant changes from its predecessor, **SHA-1**.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-256 and SHA-512 are hash functions whose digests are eight 32-bit and 64-bit words, respectively.
[src:crypto/sha-2] They use different shift amounts and additive constants, but their structures are otherwise virtually identical, differing only in the number of rounds.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-224 and SHA-384 are truncated versions of SHA-256 and SHA-512 respectively, computed with different initial values.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-512/224 and SHA-512/256 are also truncated versions of SHA-512, but the initial values are generated using the method described in Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) PUB 180-4.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-2 was first published by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) as a U.S. federal standard.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The SHA-2 family of algorithms are patented in the U.S.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The United States has released the patent under a royalty-free license.
[src:crypto/sha-2] As of 2024, the **SHA-2** cryptographic hash function remains secure against known attacks, including those from quantum computers.
[src:crypto/sha-2] With the publication of FIPS PUB 180-2, NIST added three additional hash functions in the SHA family.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The algorithms are collectively known as SHA-2, named after their digest lengths (in bits): SHA-256, SHA-384, and SHA-512.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The algorithms were first published in 2001 in the draft FIPS PUB 180-2, at which time public review and comments were accepted.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In August 2002, FIPS PUB 180-2 became the new Secure Hash Standard, replacing FIPS PUB 180-1, which was released in April 1995.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The updated standard included the original SHA-1 algorithm, with updated technical notation consistent with that describing the inner workings of the SHA-2 family.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In February 2004, a change notice was published for FIPS PUB 180-2, specifying an additional variant, SHA-224, defined to match the key length of two-key Triple DES.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In October 2008, the standard was updated in FIPS PUB 180-3, including SHA-224 from the change notice, but otherwise making no fundamental changes to the standard.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The primary motivation for updating the standard was relocating security information about the hash algorithms and recommendations for their use to Special Publications 800-107 and 800-57.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Detailed test data and example message digests were also removed from the standard, and provided as separate documents.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In March 2012, the standard was updated in FIPS PUB 180-4, adding the hash functions SHA-512/224 and SHA-512/256, and describing a method for generating initial values for truncated versions of SHA-512.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Additionally, a restriction on padding the input data prior to hash calculation was removed, allowing hash data to be calculated simultaneously with content generation, such as a real-time video or audio feed.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Padding the final data block must still occur prior to hash output.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In July 2012, NIST revised SP800-57, which provides guidance for cryptographic key management.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The publication disallowed creation of digital signatures with a hash security lower than 112 bits after 2013.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The previous revision from 2007 specified the cutoff to be the end of 2010.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In August 2012, NIST revised SP800-107 in the same manner.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In March 2023, NIST announced its decision to revise FIPS 180-4.
[src:crypto/sha-2] FIPS 180-5 will remove the SHA-1 specification, add guidance from SP 800-107, and include editorial updates.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The NIST hash function competition selected a new hash function, SHA-3, in 2012.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The SHA-3 algorithm is not derived from SHA-2.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The SHA-2 hash function is implemented in some widely used security applications and protocols, including TLS and SSL, PGP, SSH, S/MIME, and IPsec.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The inherent computational demand of SHA-2 algorithms has driven the proposal of more efficient solutions, such as those based on application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) hardware accelerators.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-256 is used for authenticating Debian software packages and in the DKIM message signing standard; SHA-512 is part of a system to authenticate archival video from the International Criminal Tribunal of the Rwandan genocide.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Linux distributions usually use 512-bit SHA-2 for secure password hashing.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Several cryptocurrencies, including Bitcoin, use SHA-256 for verifying transactions and calculating proof of work or proof of stake.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The rise of ASIC SHA-2 accelerator chips has led to the use of scrypt-based proof-of-work schemes.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In both 4G and 5G mobile networks, HMAC-SHA-256 is utilized as a key derivation function (KDF) to generate cryptographic keys essential for securing communications.
[src:crypto/sha-2] This process is defined in the 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) Technical Specifications TS 33.401 and TS 33.501, which outline the security architecture and procedures for these networks.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-1, SHA-2, and SHA-3 are the Secure Hash Algorithms required by law for use in certain U.S.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Government applications, including use within other cryptographic algorithms and protocols, for the protection of sensitive unclassified information.
[src:crypto/sha-2] FIPS PUB 180-1 also encouraged adoption and use of SHA-1 by private and commercial organizations.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-1 is being retired for most government uses; the U.S.
[src:crypto/sha-2] National Institute of Standards and Technology says, "NIST recommends that federal agencies transition away from SHA-1 for all applications as soon as possible.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Federal agencies should use SHA-2 or SHA-3 as an alternative to SHA-1.".
[src:crypto/sha-2] NIST's directive that U.S. government agencies ought to, but not explicitly must, stop uses of SHA-1 after 2010 was hoped to accelerate migration away from SHA-1.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The SHA-2 functions were not quickly adopted initially, despite better security than SHA-1.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Reasons might include lack of support for SHA-2 on systems running Windows XP SP2 or older and a lack of perceived urgency since SHA-1 collisions had not yet been found.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The Google Chrome team announced a plan to make their web browser gradually stop honoring SHA-1-dependent TLS certificates over a period from late 2014 and early 2015.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Similarly, Microsoft announced that Internet Explorer and Edge [Legacy] would stop honoring public SHA-1-signed TLS certificates from February 2017.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Mozilla disabled SHA-1 in Firefox during early January 2016, but had to re-enable it temporarily via an update, after problems with web-based user interfaces of some router models and security appliances.
[src:crypto/sha-2] For a hash function for which *L* is the number of bits in the message digest, finding a message that corresponds to a given message digest can always be done using a brute force search in 2*L* evaluations.
[src:crypto/sha-2] This is called a preimage attack and may or may not be practical depending on *L* and the particular computing environment.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The second criterion, finding two different messages that produce the same message digest, known as a collision, requires on average only 2*L*/2 evaluations using a birthday attack.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Some of the applications that use cryptographic hashes, such as password storage, are only minimally affected by a collision attack.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Constructing a password that works for a given account requires a preimage attack, as well as access to the hash of the original password (typically in the `shadow` file) which may or may not be trivial.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Reversing password encryption (e.g., to obtain a password to try against a user's account elsewhere) is not made possible by the attacks.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In the case of document signing, an attacker could not simply fake a signature from an existing document—the attacker would have to produce a pair of documents, one innocuous and one damaging, and get the private key holder to sign the innocuous document.
[src:crypto/sha-2] There are practical circumstances in which this is possible; until the end of 2008, it was possible to create forged SSL certificates using an MD5 collision which would be accepted by widely used web browsers.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Increased interest in cryptographic hash analysis during the SHA-3 competition produced several new attacks on the SHA-2 family, the best of which are given in the table below.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Only the collision attacks are of practical complexity; none of the attacks extend to the full round hash function.
[src:crypto/sha-2] At FSE 2012, researchers at Sony gave a presentation suggesting pseudo-collision attacks could be extended to 52 rounds on SHA-256 and 57 rounds on SHA-512 by building upon the biclique pseudo-preimage attack.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Implementations of all FIPS-approved security functions can be officially validated through the CMVP program, jointly run by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and the Communications Security Establishment (CSE).
[src:crypto/sha-2] For informal verification, a package to generate a high number of test vectors is made available for download on the NIST site; the resulting verification, however, does not replace the formal CMVP validation, which is required by law for certain applications.
[src:crypto/sha-2] As of December 2013, there are over 1300 validated implementations of SHA-256 and over 900 of SHA-512, with only 5 of them being capable of handling messages with a length in bits not a multiple of eight while supporting both variants.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Hash values of an empty string (i.e., a zero-length input text).
[src:crypto/sha-2] Even a small change in the message will (with overwhelming probability) result in a different hash, due to the avalanche effect.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Pseudocode for the SHA-256 algorithm follows.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Note the great increase in mixing between bits of the `w[16..63]` words compared to SHA-1.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The computation of the `ch` and `maj` values can be optimized the same way as described for SHA-1.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The *SHA-512/t IV generation function* evaluates a *modified SHA-512* on the ASCII string "SHA-512/*t*", substituted with the decimal representation of *t*.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The *modified SHA-512* is the same as SHA-512 except its initial values `h0` through `h7` have each been XORed with the hexadecimal constant `0xa5a5a5a5a5a5a5a5`.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Sample C implementation for SHA-2 family of hash functions can be found in RFC 6234.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In the table below, *internal state* means the "internal hash sum" after each compression of a data block.
[src:crypto/sha-2] In the bitwise operations column, "Rot" stands for rotate no carry, and "Shr" stands for right logical shift.
[src:crypto/sha-2] All of these algorithms employ modular addition in some fashion except for SHA-3.
[src:crypto/sha-2] More detailed performance measurements on modern processor architectures are given in the table below.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The performance numbers labeled 'x86' were running using 32-bit code on 64-bit processors, whereas the 'x86-64' numbers are native 64-bit code.
[src:crypto/sha-2] While SHA-256 is designed for 32-bit calculations, it does benefit from code optimized for 64-bit processors on the x86 architecture.
[src:crypto/sha-2] 32-bit implementations of SHA-512 are significantly slower than their 64-bit counterparts.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Variants of both algorithms with different output sizes will perform similarly, since the message expansion and compression functions are identical, and only the initial hash values and output sizes are different.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The best implementations of MD5 and SHA-1 perform between 4.5 and 6 cycles per byte on modern processors.
[src:crypto/sha-2] Testing was performed by the University of Illinois at Chicago on their hydra8 system running an Intel Xeon E3-1275 V2 at a clock speed of 3.5 GHz, and on their hydra9 system running an AMD A10-5800K APU at a clock speed of 3.8 GHz.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The referenced cycles per byte speeds above are the median performance of an algorithm digesting a 4,096 byte message using the SUPERCOP cryptographic benchmarking software.
[src:crypto/sha-2] The MiB/s performance is extrapolated from the CPU clockspeed on a single core; real-world performance will vary due to a variety of factors.
[src:crypto/sha-2] SHA-256 and SHA-512 are vulnerable to a length extension attack, but SHA-384 and SHA-256/512 are not vulnerable because their output is a truncated version of their internal state.
